# =============================================================================
# wtfjs — Denys Dovhan's "🤪 A list of funny and tricky
#          JavaScript examples" — a Node.js CLI that displays
#          random "WTF JS" examples in your terminal.  Wtfjs
#          is the canonical catalog of JavaScript weirdness +
#          quirks + counterintuitive behaviors that the
#          language exhibits due to its coercion rules + ECMA
#          spec history.  The project includes hundreds of
#          documented WTF examples like:
#              [] + []      // ''
#              [] + {}      // '[object Object]'
#              {} + []      // 0 (in some contexts)
#              true + true  // 2
#              0.1 + 0.2    // 0.30000000000000004
#              Number(null) // 0  but  Number(undefined) // NaN
#              typeof NaN   // 'number'
#              "5" - 3      // 2  but  "5" + 3 // "53"
#              [1, 2] == "1,2"  // true
#              true == 1    // true  but  true === 1 // false
#          The CLI fetches the random examples from the
#          repository's README.md (which serves both as
#          GitHub documentation AND as the data source for
#          the terminal display).  Supports MULTIPLE LANGUAGES
#          via --lang flag — translations into pt-br, zh-cn,
#          fr-fr, it-it, ko, hi, pl, si.
#
# Author:  Denys Dovhan (Ukrainian engineer, Apple software
#          engineer, creator of zsh themes spaceship-prompt
#          + zsh-async + zsh-history-substring-search) +
#          200+ international contributors who maintain the
#          README + translations + new WTF examples.
# Source:  https://github.com/denysdovhan/wtfjs
#          https://github.com/denysdovhan/wtfjs/blob/master/wtfjs.js
# CLI:     wtfjs.js — uses `meow` (already documented in
#          taxonomy) for argv parsing.  Headline visual
#          library: `boxen` (sindresorhus/boxen) for the
#          framed-box rendering of WTF JS examples in the
#          terminal.
# Library: boxen (sindresorhus/boxen)
#          ("Create boxes in the terminal" — Sindre Sorhus —
#           released 2015 as the canonical Node.js library for
#           rendering FRAMED BOXES around terminal text.  Used
#           by update-notifier (Sindre's update-checking
#           library) to display the iconic "Update available!"
#           boxes that appear in npm install output, by
#           thousands of CLI tools for banner/intro displays,
#           by wrap-cli for content emphasis, and by
#           interactive prompts for visual section delimiters.
#           boxen's API is centered on the `boxen(text,
#           options)` function returning a STRING with the
#           rendered box — caller is responsible for printing
#           it.  Supports rich customization:
#             - 10+ built-in border styles (single, double,
#               round, bold, classic, etc)
#             - Custom borders via character map
#             - Padding + margin
#             - Background colors (16-color + RGB)
#             - Border colors (chalk-style strings)
#             - Title text positioned in border
#             - Alignment (left/center/right)
#             - Full-width mode (terminal-width)
#             - Multi-line text with proper centering)
# License: MIT (wtfjs); MIT (boxen)
# Status:  wtfjs — 37605+ stars on denysdovhan/wtfjs (top-200
