#
# WHAT IS boxen AND WHY IS IT THE 57TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# boxen (https://github.com/sindresorhus/boxen, 3300+ stars) is
# **Sindre Sorhus's "create boxes in the terminal"** — the
# foundational Node.js library for rendering framed boxes around
# terminal text.  Released 2015.  Part of Sindre's 1500+ package
# Node ecosystem alongside ora (R596) + chalk + meow + figures +
# log-symbols + cli-spinners.  boxen is the BOX-RENDERING
# COMPONENT of the npm update notification "Update available!"
# yellow boxes that appear when packages have new versions.
#
# boxen's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. FUNCTION-RETURNS-STRING DESIGN — boxen's API is centered
#      on the `boxen(text, options)` function that RETURNS a
#      STRING with the rendered box.  The CALLER decides what
#      to do with the string (print, save, send via API, etc):
#
#          import boxen from 'boxen';
#
#          const box = boxen('Hello, world!', {
#              padding: 1,
#              margin: 1,
#              borderStyle: 'double',
#              borderColor: 'cyan',
#              backgroundColor: '#555',
#              align: 'center',
#              title: 'Greeting',
#              titleAlignment: 'left',
#          });
#
#          console.log(box);
#          //   ╔═════ Greeting ═════╗
#          //   ║                     ║
#          //   ║   Hello, world!     ║
#          //   ║                     ║
#          //   ╚═════════════════════╝
#
#      Compare:
#         * blessed: direct terminal manipulation
#         * cli-boxes: just border-character data, no rendering
#         * boxen: FUNCTION-RETURNS-STRING with rich customization
#      FIRST documented TS-Node box-rendering library with
#      function-returns-string design.
#
#   2. TEN+ BUILT-IN BORDER STYLES — boxen ships with multiple
#      pre-defined border-character sets:
#         * single — basic single-line: ┌─┐ │ │ └─┘
#         * double — double-line: ╔═╗ ║ ║ ╚═╝
#         * round — rounded corners: ╭─╮ │ │ ╰─╯
#         * bold — heavy lines: ┏━┓ ┃ ┃ ┗━┛
#         * singleDouble — single sides, double top/bottom
#         * doubleSingle — double sides, single top/bottom
#         * classic — ASCII-only: +-+ | | +-+
#         * arrow — arrow corners: ←→↑↓
#         * none — no visible border (for padding only)
#         * Plus CUSTOM border via character map
#      Compare:
#         * cli-boxes: same character sets (boxen depends on it)
#         * Other libs: ASCII-only or limited styles
#         * boxen: 10+ pre-built + custom-character maps
#      FIRST documented TS-Node library with 10+ pre-built
#      border styles.
#
#   3. TITLE TEXT IN BORDER — boxen supports a TITLE positioned
#      within the top border:
#
#          boxen('Body text', {
#              title: 'Section Title',
#              titleAlignment: 'left',    // 'left' / 'center' / 'right'
#              borderStyle: 'double',
#          });
#          //   ╔═ Section Title ═════════╗
#          //   ║ Body text                ║
#          //   ╚══════════════════════════╝
#
#      Compare every other documented terminal-box library —
#      most lack title-in-border feature.  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node terminal-box library with title-in-border.
#
#   4. PADDING + MARGIN INDEPENDENT CONTROL — boxen supports
#      both PADDING (inside the box, between border and text)
#      and MARGIN (outside the box, before/after in stdout):
#
#          boxen('Text', {
#              padding: { top: 1, bottom: 1, left: 4, right: 4 },
#              margin: { top: 2, bottom: 1, left: 0, right: 0 },
#          });
#
#      Or shorthand:
#
#          boxen('Text', { padding: 1, margin: 1 });
#
#      Compare:
#         * cli-boxes: no padding/margin (just border chars)
#         * blessed: padding via box element attributes
#         * boxen: padding + margin INDEPENDENT CSS-style
#                   shorthand + individual sides
#      FIRST documented TS-Node box library with CSS-style
#      padding + margin shorthand.
#
#   5. UPDATE-NOTIFIER PROVENANCE — boxen is the BOX-RENDERING
#      COMPONENT of update-notifier (also by Sindre Sorhus),
#      the library used by ~10,000 npm packages to display the
#      iconic "Update available!" yellow box after invocation:
#
#                ╭──────────────────────────────────╮
#                │                                    │
#                │   Update available 1.2.3 → 1.3.0   │
#                │   Run npm i -g pkg to update       │
#                │                                    │
#                ╰──────────────────────────────────╯
#
#      That box is rendered by boxen.  When you've seen one of
#      these in your terminal (and every Node developer has,
#      hundreds of times), you've seen boxen's output.  Major
#      transitive adopters via update-notifier:
#         * yo (Yeoman scaffolder)
#         * @angular/cli
#         * vue-cli (legacy)
#         * @netlify/cli
#         * heroku-cli
#         * gulp-cli
#         * mocha (early versions)
#         * Many AWS CLI tools
#         * Many GitHub CLI extensions
#         * wtfjs (THIS — Denys Dovhan's JS-weirdness catalog)
#      FIRST documented TS-Node library with update-notifier
#      transitive provenance (10000+ npm packages).
#
# boxen's relationship to other documented TS-Node libraries:
#
#   * Like chalk/kleur/picocolors/ansis — all from the
#                                          Sindresorhus or
#                                          related ecosystems
#   * Unlike colorizers — boxen wraps text with FRAMES; the
#                          colorizers add color to text content
#   * Like ink (R532) + blessed (R536) — all do TUI rendering
#   * Unlike ink/blessed — boxen is a SINGLE-FUNCTION widget;
#                           ink/blessed are full TUI frameworks
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust: indicatif's "ProgressBar with steady tick"
#                  doesn't quite match
#         * Go: charmbracelet/lipgloss .Border() method — direct
#                Go analog (boxen-style border rendering)
#         * Python: rich.panel — Python's box-rendering library
#                    with same role
#     boxen is the FIRST documented TS-Node single-purpose
#     terminal-box rendering library with function-returns-
#     string + 10+ border styles + title-in-border + CSS-style
#     padding/margin + update-notifier provenance.
#
